 of conflicts within its original region. It shows how in face of the growing threat of global warming the EBRD, working mainly with the private sector, developed a sustainable energy business model to tackle climate change.Transforming Markets also examines how the EBRD broadened its investment criteria, arguing that transition towards sustainable economies requires market qualities that are not only competitive and integrated but which are also resilient, well-governed, green and more inclusive. This approach aligned with the 2015 Paris Agreement and the international community's 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development, with its core set of 17 sustainable development goals. The story of the EBRD's own transition and rich history provides a route map for building the sustainable markets necessary for future growth and prosperity.  afunded by European Bank for Reconstruction and Development  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDevelopment bankszEurope. 0aEconomic development projectszEurope. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Banks & Banking.2bisacsh  aglobal and regional crises.  asustainable economies.  asustainable energy business model.1 aKilpatrick, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRenaud-Basso, Odile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Anthony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWilliams, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aEuropean Bank for Reconstruction and Developmentefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCen